The architects saw - a kindergarten is part of the office
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been open to Arch. Design staff since last year.
From the very beginning, the design and architecture firm Arch.Design, whose studios have provided a number of well-known Brno buildings, counted on the premises for its company mini-kindergarten from the very first designs for the new building Avriopoint.
Wisely, because most of its 90 employees are baby boomers, and the company is keen to get the project developers back to work as soon as possible.
Along with the possibility to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This will make it easier for civil engineers and architects to combine their demanding careers with caring for children.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of Arch. Design's staff, and with the help of management, they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from funds provided by the European Social Fund and from the State budget of the Czech Republic.
This funding (grants amounting to CZK 2.8 million) enabled the necessary equipment to be provided, as well as providing qualified staff and operations for a period of two years.
After having exhausted the funding (for 2 years), the company Arch.Design is obligated to continue running the mini-kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
Preparing for this project took a whole year, with Economy Rating providing active assistance in processing the applications.
The children are looked after by full-time qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher. Children in kindergarten can attend the kindergarten without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, although several children take turns playing during the day.
The nursery is flexibly adjusted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights regarding the use of the nursery, regardless of the company's hierarchy and their respective positions.
Although it is about individual education and care, the content of the programme in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but also receive excellent instruction - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, as well as English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a calculator available for children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can always have a look at the children, thus avoiding the stress of having to pick the children up late from a kindergarten that is far away.
Parents are therefore using their working time more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships develop here too.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, family-friendly programs that strengthen their HR marketing.
A bone house still fascinates even after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudí.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs are like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are cracked fish-mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The house with its organic forms was nicknamed '& quot; Bonehouse' by locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splints and mosaics, the shed-like facades and the ubiquitous soft lines are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures, which remind of nature and living beings.
Only on closer inspection does one realize that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm, and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole façade appears even more vivid, more dramatic, and the special illumination adds to the brilliance of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Wavy shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, door ornaments, even peepholes and moldings.
Batlló is located in the Eixample district, on the lively Passeig de Grácia shopping street at No. 43. Batlló was created through the remodeling of a house dating back to 1877, designed by Emilio Sala Cortese.
Reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new one, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudi's idea of an unusual and also cheaper remodeling.
However, the apartment building Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his drawing board that the decorations for the owner's representative apartment were created, and his idea was also to use mosaics on the façade.
However, numerous other artists and artists also contributed to the design of the façade.
Working together on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
This is how Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá in Güell Park, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed 'quot; bonehead' by locals for its organic shapes.
Others called it the & quot; yawning house & quot; due to the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building there is the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house at the time, featuring ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Their 45 degree tilt already seems somewhat bizarre.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all building regulations of the time and did not let himself be deterred by these.
Before construction started, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city's fathers were so shocked by the result when it was completed two years later that they demanded a remedy.
The councillors were offended by the fact that the building, with its pillars, even interfered with the public pavement.
However, there have been no changes; on the contrary, only fifteen days after the district requested this, Josep Batlló submitted a request for permission to lease the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a parlour, on the 3rd floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor has been leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building passes through a staircase up to the rooftop terrace.
By the basic elements of the conversion, all right-angles and straight lines were eliminated and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of the interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors, allowing a larger company to chat comfortably, without having to give up a certain intimacy for more private conversations.
In addition to a new façade, the house was renovated by Gaudí and given a rather unusual roof and two further floors.
Gaudí's play with light is also impressive, as are the blue and white glazed tiles covering the courtyard and the atriums of light.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply applied the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colours, which, on the contrary, absorb the sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, inscribed in UNESCO's World Heritage List in 2005, is now open to everyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is opened to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was determined that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were retained, and even extended to further common rooms and the attic rooms, including the rooftop terrace.
The price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard cut, it is 16,50 Euro, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get 20% reduction.
This amount exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to experience the real atmosphere of the house with its little dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the inhabitants of the house and visit him at home.
