The system, which was invented to search for cars, can also locate human beings, which is useful in cases like the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette packet, but it soon won 't be any bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people are terrified by the case of Anička, who disappeared, and so they are looking for ways and means to better protect their children.
Also at the price of an infringement of their privacy.
& quot; We try to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about an effective means to reduce the likelihood of tragedy, cites Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
& quot; I acknowledge that in isolated cases, such devices may be misused, for example, putting it in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not had any such case. & quot;
& quot; Most customers really purchase it for security reasons, adds Pilin.
However, he believes that the child should always know what the & quot; box is for, and how to use it in case of emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, they simply get rid of them.
& quot; Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things when they do not want to be controlled. & quot;
& quot; Mobile phones raised great expectations among parents at first, but they are just as easy to turn off as these new & quot; surveillance devices, notes Ms. Bočková.
In her opinion, it is also disputed whether such an institution actually helps in case of an attack.
& quot; During planned kidnappings, the kidnapper virtually always checks if the child has any electronics with him or her that could be used to locate him or her. & quot;
& quot; Today it's the mobile phone. & quot;
& quot; If such monitoring devices were to be used more widely, they would also seek them, since their sale would surely be accompanied by massive advertising. & quot;
& quot; In these cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police, notes the psychologist.
However, it acknowledges that similar devices can be useful in the event of a sudden attack by a paedophile.
According to Roberta Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for cars as well as individuals, the existence of such a device may help even if it is destroyed immediately after the attack.
& quot; This is because the device can be configured to report the position of the device at certain intervals. & quot;
& quot; Even if it were destroyed immediately, at least the last position of the affected person is available. & quot;
& quot; On more expensive devices, a clinometer is built in, which means that if you fall and remain motionless, the device will immediately send a warning indicating the position of & quot;, claims Mr. Čech.
In his opinion, similar services could be provided by smart mobile phones with navigation, all you have to do is download some special software.
The problem with the current tracking devices is that they are either match-box-sized devices that resemble trailers, or smaller ones.
There is always a danger of losing them.
Therefore, according to Mr Pilin of Macro Weil, devices that look like normal digital watches are currently being tested.
& quot; This has the advantage that the potential attacker does not have to know that he or she is dealing with a monitoring or locating device.
& quot; Or he only notices this after a certain amount of time, which gives the police a head start. & quot;, he adds.
No matter in which direction the trend is headed, towards wristbands or pendants, the same technology is always used as for vehicle locating.
This is a combination of the location function using the GPS system (the same as with the car satnav) and the function of a mobile phone that reports the current position.
The army has so many cords that you could wrap whole Czech Republic around it, but it would only last two years
The Czech army purchased 445 km of fuses to detonate with IEDs.
The year before, the Ministry of Defense had already delivered 224 kilometers of fuse cord to the army camps.
It is comforting to know that the Armed Forces have served for 225 years.
The problem is only the durability of the fuses - two years, but no more than four.
The army bought the fuses from the public limited company STV Group, a. s., for a paltry 40 million kronor.
In its justification for purchasing this enormous amount of fuse, the General Staff of MF DNES replied that the soldiers consume approximately 60 kilometers of fuse annually.
According to research by army pyrotechnicians, which MF DNES raised, this figure shows that the whole army has to undergo an extremely intensive pyrotechnical training every year, from all the generals and officers of the army command, to the secretaries and cleaners.
Defense Minister Alexandr Vondra and Army Gen. Vlastimil Picek were not exempt.
Only in this way can the considerable annual consumption of sixty kilometres of ignition cords be partially justified.
This length corresponds to 25.000 detonations.
But even so, these armies would last for more than a decade.
However, if the old rule of experts is still applicable, that for the training of each new professional soldier two meters of fuse will suffice, then with these new purchases - also in view of the increased need of the Pioneer and Special Forces - the army has created a calming supply for the aforementioned 225 years.
Soldiers from the Rapid Deployment Brigade recently complained to the Minister of Defense, Vondra, that they almost ran out of small arms cartridges, so that practice shooting is severely restricted due to a lack of resources.
Not to mention the lack of underpants.
& quot; Nor can I fathom why they are buying such vast quantities of ignition cords from us. & quot;
But that is ultimately up to them, they will know what they need them for. & quot;
& quot; The army is a good customer for us, and we as the trader want to meet it as best we can, says Jan Děcký, STV Group Sales Manager.
Jan Pejšek, spokesman of the Ministry of Defense, justified the purchase of hundreds of kilometers of fuse by saying that this would have kept the army stocking up with this & quot; ammunition for at least 10 years.
Jan Děcký of the STV Group only speaks of a four-year service life of the fuses, and the police and army pyrotechnician only speaks of a two-year service life.
& quot; With perfect storage, the four years mentioned are probably possible, admits one of them, who wishes to remain anonymous so as not to be accused of criticizing the army.
At the end of their useful life, any type of ammunition must be thoroughly tested to see if it is still reliable or if it will endanger the lives of the soldiers.
These tests are not free of charge, they cost additional money.
Another argument of the Ministry of Defence is the quantity discount for the 445 kilometer fuse.
& quot; They cost us sixty percent less than last year's delivery of 244 kilometers', spokesman Pejšek informs us of the position of the purchasers from the Ministry of Defence.
Just for comparison: for some years now, the annual consumption of cord ignitions by police pyrotechnicians liquidating ammunition from World War II or the Soviet fraternal army has barely exceeded 1,500 meters.
And the police always order only those quantities of ammunition that can be used up before the period of use ends.
Already for the safety of the pyrotechnicians, one keeps open the possibility for flexible purchases of more modern and therefore also reliable ignitions.
The Ministry of Defence is already facing huge problems in winding up tens of thousands of tonnes of ammunition from the Warsaw Treaty, as the two hundred thousand-strong Czechoslovak People's Army prepared to march on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians mentioned by MF DNES, in a few years' time the Czech Armed Forces will have the same problem with liquidating hundreds of kilometres' old fuses that they now purchase cheaply.
