Household housing costs are rising by a few hundred per month
From January onwards, households will not only have to face higher costs for all types of energy, but will also have to pay higher water and waste water charges, as well as higher rents for district heating and in some places rents.
As of January, families will have to withdraw several hundred kroner more per month from their wallet than before.
Electricity will be up to 4.6% more expensive, gas will be up to 2% more expensive, in some cities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supplies, and in some places district heating will be more expensive.
The cost of electricity alone is increasing by several hundred kronor per year.
The high-voltage electricity prices were lowered by all main suppliers, which is mainly due to the significant promotion of electricity generation from renewable sources, namely photovoltaic systems.
Gas will become only moderately more expensive, but only when people need to heat the most and have the highest consumption.
Here too, one can expect a few hundred more kronor per year.
While electricity and gas become more expensive throughout the Czech Republic, district heating prices vary from city to city.
Larger cities, in particular, are planning price increases.
For example, from January households in Pardubice and Hradec Králové will have to pay up to 50 kronor more per month for district heating, and families in Liberec will pay more than 1000 kronor more per year.
The inhabitants of Prague, on the other hand, face 9% higher water and sewerage charges if the city increases the infrastructure rent.
If the rent does not change, it is only 6.8 percent.
However, the price in Prague remains among the lowest in the whole of the Czech Republic.
In Northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and waste water charges will increase by 7.4%.
Huge increases in rents are to be expected in 140,000 rental apartments, for example, for which the so-called rent regulation ceases to apply from January onwards.
For example, CPI Byty, which owns 2500 apartments in Ústí nad Labem, plans to increase rents by 100% from January onwards.
The company wants to take legal action against anyone who does not agree to this rent increase.
Regulated rents, which are still paid in nearly 300,000 homes, are expected to rise by more than 10 per cent next year.
