Longer index finger than ring finger means lower risk of developing cancer
Men who have a longer index finger than the ring finger are obviously less likely to develop prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is said to be linked to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
& quot; Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty years old. & quot;, said the study's co-author, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should definitely undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health issues, Ms Eeles added.
Between 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, as well as 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study participants, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men were as likely to develop prostate cancer as 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, this risk decreased by 33 percent for men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, and even decreased by 87 percent for men up to the age of sixty.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which form already in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone equals a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that it is precisely testosterone that accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Czech Academy of Sciences, said he was briefly familiar with the study, but he does not think the relationship between finger length and cancer risk was' fully proven '.
