The democracy movement in Latin America is gaining strength, as is support for private enterprises.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These are the results of the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, thus showing the change of opinion in this region.
There are two facts that catch the eye of & apos;'s respondents in this year' s September and October Poll.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its major institutions.
In numerous countries along the South American Pacific Coast, the democratic movement has increased sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown at an annual rate of 6% since 2002, pro-democracy support increased from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy is recovering from last year's sharp decline.
Yet only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are staunch Democrats, lowering the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practices, the same number as last year but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
Some 34% trust their country's Congress and 45% trust their government. Both values are the same as last year but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts to become more democratic.
This continued during the Great Depression, possibly because the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession, and recovered quickly.
Moreover, the poor were absorbed by a stronger social safety net.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America increased only slightly in 2009, and fell by 32% again this year.)
However, there are strong differences in sentiment from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy, and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more pronounced and violent crime increased.
For only the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they or a family member became a victim of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, the levels have decreased, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The rising economic performance is reflected in increased support for the private and market economy: approximately 71% of respondents nationwide reported that the private sector is indispensable for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly enough, 62% of respondents in Venezuela maintained this view (and 80% are in favor of private sector ownership), despite the fact that its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, nationalizes many private companies.
Brazil has the most weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
By contrast, respondents in Mexico and most of Central America see the US as the most influential country, with Venezuela taking over the role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
