The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered essential to life.
& quot; This organism has two possibilities. & quot;
& quot; He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow. & quot;
& quot; This makes it something very special, even though it is almost a kind of & apos; alien & apos; way of life, said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online edition of the journal Science on Thursday.
To date, six main elements have been considered essential for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But, as the scientists discovered, the bacterium continues to grow in Mono Lake, California, even if it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
& quot; It makes you wonder what else is possible,'said the report' s co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for alien life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study deals with microbes that have been found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can start biochemical processes with the help of other elements, and that the & apos; standard elements, which we believe are absolutely essential for life, are not necessarily pre-defined & quot;, explained Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
& quot; This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another, & quot; added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Astrobiological Institute of NASA, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
As arsenic and phosphorus chemically resemble each other, she assumed that microbes exposed to both might be able to replace one element with another.
& quot; The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus. & quot;
& quot; This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from the other. & quot;
& quot; But the difference is so great that arsenic has a different effect to phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it smears just about everything. & quot; explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
While the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, Lecturer in Microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea of replacing phosphorus with arsenic is nothing new, but there's no working example yet.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so's why scientists believe early life forms used it.
& quot; This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently from the Early Earth Age, said & quot;'s Forster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
Research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
