Prosecutor will not indict Senator Ensign
Prosecutors from the Justice Department have acquitted Senator John Ensign of charges stemming from his affair with a former campaign aide and his attempt to lobby her husband, the senator's attorneys announced Wednesday.
This decision brings to an end the most serious allegation against Senator Ensign, the Nevada Republican. Until the scandal made national headlines and dampened his career, he was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012.
Senator Ensign's office announced that it was pleased with the verdict after a year-long investigation.
The Senate Ethics Committee, however, could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign's attorneys, they have been notified by the Department of Justice that the investigation into Senator Ensign has been terminated and that no further charges have been filed in this matter.
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The ruling came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there was ample evidence Ensign violated the lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents, first revealed in the New York Times in October 2009, gave rise to speculation that Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, one of his campaign aides, win lucrative contracts to buy his silence about an affair with Hamptons wife Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as Ensign's treasurer during an election campaign.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton work. According to the documents and interrogations, he lobbied Hamptons for her after she was hired.
Because Hampton was recently on Ensign's election team, he was not allowed to lobby for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called revolving door lobbying ban.
According to the published circumstantial evidence, & quot; appears to be collusion and violation of the revolving door bylaws, 'according to Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients targeted by the government.
While the Justice Department officially declined to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics attorneys said the department seemed very cautious about accepting political charges after a series of defeats that were followed by the media with great interest, including the decision last year to drop charges of misconduct by the prosecutor against former Senator Ted Stevens.
Prosecutors are obviously terrible & quot;, said Melanie Sloan, president of & quot; Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington & quot; (an organization whose goal is to fight corruption in U.S. parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers that brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to court.
& quot; This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the law does not apply to them, & quot; she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day, informing him that the department would not bring charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defense attorneys had worked with prosecutors to convince them that the senator acted in accordance with the law, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday.
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he had made to prosecutors.
& quot; I am not comfortable going into the details of the talks between the Department of Justice and myself. That being said, we think we made the right decision & quot;, "he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to close its investigation into a separate lawsuit by the ethics group alleging that a $96,000 payment by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was anything more than a gift.
NV Energy, a large company in Nevada that long supported the senator, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbying work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
