Can courtesy connect the divider?
After a campaign of swear words and negativity, little civility has broken out in Washington this week.
Is this the omen of genuine two-party cooperation, or a moment of illusion, before quickly returning to the fighting of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders failed to produce a breakthrough on major issues to be dealt with during the so-called' lame duck session '.
By all accounts, it was not a polite discussion between two different sides, nor a consideration of their shared responsibilities to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan point-scoring.
The president's deficit commission's public meeting Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the policy differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that obscures the ideological chasm that continues to divide members.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has dawned.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one asks for the other to show signs of willingness to cooperate and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after another bout of partisan warfare.
Therefore, Tuesday's meeting itself and its assessment by the attendees was limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the last two years.
Whether it is taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Finally, the November election softened Washington's mood, at least for a short period of time.
& quot; No question, the tone has changed & quot;, said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for & quot; Ethics and Public Policy Center.
& quot; This is inevitable after elections.
Elections awaken partisan passions that die again.
And that's a good thing.
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of & quot; lame duck session & quot;, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution. & quot;
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and nobody advocates them.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or all of them, temporary or permanent.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe that they are favoring tax cuts for the rich while denying assistance to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there has been a growing optimism that these issues can be agreed upon during the & quot; lame duck session & quot;, while also ratifying the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of Brookings Insitution warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues of lame duck session & quot; need not necessarily lead to enduring cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
& quot; After the things that need to be done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation & quot;, "he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
& quot; I see much that happens from now until 2012, as a pre-match, or shadow-boxing, for the main event of 2012 & quot;, 'he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the make-up of the new Republican majority in the White House, and with the tea party voters who were instrumental in their formation.
As concerned as Republican leaders may be about playing too much poker, they know they have to try to deliver on their promises to cut government spending and repeal health care reform.
These party lines are already apparent in the initial reactions regarding the deficit commission's recommendations, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and reducing government expenditure.
Vice Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington, and have, by their own estimation, pushed the deficit issue so hard into the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation, and they are fighting hard to get anywhere near that number.
The greatest opposition is found in the elected representatives of the body, because on financial issues, at least now, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take the form of party clashes next year, when Republicans will challenge Obama over the state's budget, taxes, and health-care system, followed later by a period of more bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It is proven that despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
When confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, both parties must be careful about the public reaction.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and appear to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and the congressional Republicans than was once between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a much more consequential election in 2012.
Seen this way, the civility displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator on the issues that still divide the two.
