& quot; Everyone here loves Ta Mok. & quot;
& quot; He was a good leader and he looked after his people & quot; said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years.
Known as & quot; the Butcher & quot; due to its brutality during the Khmer Rouge domination, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwest Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed the infrastructure and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrender to the government, longtime followers in Anlong Veng are being challenged.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation forum allowed the victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a textbook that tells the story of the Khmer Rouge for the first time to children of former soldiers.
And in July, a joint UN-Cambodian tribunal sentenced a former Khmer Rouge member for the first time, when it sentenced the former chief of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among Alnlong Veng's Khmer Rouge veterans, complicating their efforts for reconciliation and reintegration into Cambodian society.
& quot; There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything & quot; said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization researching the regime.
& quot; For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil. & quot;
& quot; It splits families. & quot;
During Khmer Rouge's rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-ed government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
Here they spread trouble until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, and Ieng Sary fought guerrilla war from their bases in the West of the Cambodian Mountains and Jungle, Ta Mok brought up the next generation in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge militants began defecting to the government, leading to the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who refused to yield, was arrested by government forces in the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh Prison, where he was awaiting trial.
When their patrons stopped protecting them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to the grinding poverty of rural Cambodia, and many held nostalgic memories of the movement.
Even though a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained local government posts because they laid down their weapons, the rank-and-file soldiers remained poor, illiterate peasants.
& quot; These people have benefited very little from capitulation, said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
