On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has proposed new adjustment measures, starting with tax breaks for small and micro-enterprises, regulating temporary work agencies or ending the 426 euro support for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefits, up to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30% of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for provoking the current crisis.
How can these operations be understood?
Let's face it, Merkel' s position is no fault of hers in public relations.
Quite the opposite, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is adopting a radically new perspective on shaping our future, one that clashes with the traditional traditions of much of its partners.
In the face of opposition in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second is the re-introduction of the Deutschmark - although it currently sounds more like science fiction - with the support of a large part of public opinion, around 50% of the population.
The third: redesigning the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishing countries that exceed the benchmarks; possibly stopping payments in some countries as well as extending the cost of potential adjustment to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been apparent for some time now. So there are no excuses now.
First, 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created deficit incentives, and the German government pulled a constitutional reform sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict fiscal plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second signal came from the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
At the time it was heavily criticized. But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the published opinion was absolutely against a bailout for Greece.
Finally, Merkel came out once again in the last few days of October with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to allow the rescue of a country while obliging private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European because it drove the Ireland crisis and everything that followed.
But its proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, was accepted. In the next few months we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line, which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old way of functioning of the euro will cease to exist from this date onwards.
2013 will be the year of the birth of a new currency area, in which infringing countries will be severely punished, may be forced to default, and in this case the private sector will have to bear some of the costs.
Germany is showing us that we must embark on a tough course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, consumption moderation, improved productivity and competitiveness, as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as advocated by Spain in the boom period, simply will not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just a matter of bringing the public deficit down to 3% of GDP by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do in these conditions is to cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence calms down.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities we are offered until spring 2013.
It appears that Zapatero understood this too, and his dual announcement (the promised reforms after last Saturday's meeting with big business, and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite criticising Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in her own house has made its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like it will change anything.
Among the possibilities being considered, we cannot rule out the possibility of leaving the euro area, which is stuffed with countries that are not serious.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and rule avoidance
Tricks like the one performed by Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax demonstrate inventiveness, but no desire to evade sanction.
The exclusion allegedly instigated by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League caused a lot of ink to be spilled over whether it was an unsportsmanlike act or not, and possibly both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
It is well known that the two players lost time a few minutes before the game ended (their team had clearly won) and committed several fouls before the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would be leading their group, the two players will meet the prescribed sanction at the next league match against Auxerre, thus entering the next phase of the game without any cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee fined the club's coach, José Mourinho, two matches and the players involved different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so prevalent that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the presented case comes from the fact that a team of the football club Real Madrid (which pretends nobility and honor in its anthem and punishes its players on other occasions for similar incidents) played the leading role in it, and from the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocation technician.
In any case, the debate is whether this type of conduct, which is not explicitly prohibited by the statutes, contravenes the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute rule circumvention. In fact, this approach conforms to the statutes of sport, but appear to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage done to the spirit of sport should be investigated.
The spirit of sportsmanship defends the physical integrity of the opponent, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from taking undue advantage of the opposition team. Again, this did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand to be a cheating or rule circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not secretly done to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible, so that it will be punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders took from the deliberate fouls.
It is important to emphasize that the rival was not placed in a less favorable position, nor were advantages sought for the game being played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players at its disposal.
The advantage, obviously, is that players go into the next phase of the Champions League season without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term advantage, unsettled to a certain extent, because the team might leave at some point. Also, this gives sanction to the players who play a card, and moves them to the second card cycle, where they leave with less than the first cycle due to accumulation.
This means that it is not so clear whether it is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices do not go against the spirit of sport, including strategic decisions to maximize the benefits of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent any sanction (this would be a clear case of rule circumvention, in fact), instead choosing when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision not to evade or escape punishment.
Although the line between inventiveness and the control environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemics arose out of two factors: because there were two self-exclusions involved, and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much of an ethical nature as of an aesthetic nature.
