In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Change Summit (COP16), Su Wei asserted that his country has made a tremendous effort to reduce carbon footprints and convert its industry.
He noted that over the last four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work with the international community on this matter.
He explained that China's climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and pilot programme support.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the objectives of reducing the emission of gases, he explained.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the states collaborated with those of the central state and municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
Furthermore, he pointed out that several multi-year plans have already been started or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those receiving funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Effective Utilization Program, which has been in place for the last five years and has received investment from the United Nations (UN), government and private hands.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, government scientific adviser on climate change in this country, confirmed that China's efforts are far greater than is commonly believed to be the case.
He pointed out that per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China are six tons per person, compared to 100 tons in the United States. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to environmental pollution.
