USA changes the rules for obtaining a visa
People need to present themselves to the visa services before they can go to the consulate for a visa application, reducing costs.
Starting from 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the embassy of the United States and in the consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to introduce themselves to the Visa Application Services (ASC), the initials in English, before being interviewed at the consulate.
ASC staff records the biometric data of the applicant, which is verified by the consulate before the call is made.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, which include:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases because there is no longer any need to pay separately for the appointment, processing the visa application and transportation service used to deliver the document.
The applicant only makes one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for request visas (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for traders and investors.
Those who only wish to renew their visa do not need to go to the consulate, they only need to go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
As the biometric data is fetched from the ASC, applicants requiring a second appointment to the consulate will be left there less than before.
Those applying for a visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey, and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service charge.
Additional information about the new visa application procedure can be found at: http: / / mexico. usembassy. gov / boletines / sp101201 _ Visas-FAQs. html
