Worldwide lighting renewal plan
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of homes, commerce and industry in 100 countries, with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (CFCs) equal to almost one third of the additional reduction that will have to be achieved in order to stabilize the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the steps of the major concrete projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun, to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments of industrialized countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs emitted from lighting on Earth would be avoided if the incandescent white bulbs, which are still a 50-70% monopoly on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or, better yet, light-emitting diodes (LED).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of world emissions.
This equals the equivalent of 70% of the exhaust emissions from the world's fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major exhaust emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans aimed at reducing global CFC emissions from 53Gt to 49Gt.
However, we would still have to subtract 5 Gt from this balance in order to stabilise the climate increase of 2 degrees Celsius from now to 2020, in order to prevent it from spiralling out of control.
In the white-incandescent bulbs 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%. With the new LED light bulbs, this energy consumption is reduced by twice as much.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10.000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched this week by the manufacturer Philips - this company, incidentally, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25.000 hours, and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an indication of the potential savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
Besides the fact that these completely new light bulbs only emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have pointed out that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury, which means that they have to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in the developing countries unless the producers provide a receiving point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not compact fluorescent bulbs, but coal-fired power stations, which emit much more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power stations emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would generate as a result of this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion annually buying electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power stations, which would cost Indonesia $2.5 billion to build.
