This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who engage in occultism believe in nothing more than what they already know, confirming what they have already learned.
This is also the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
Likewise, the Secret Files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or restricted in spirit) is also the chief of the secret service (otherwise he could be whatever, for example, the editor of Libération), who only considers what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as that that Newsweek published the week before.
So why was there such a fuss made over the disclosures in these files?
On one page, they state what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War, and since then even the Heads of Government have been able to call each other or to take a plane to meet for dinner - the embassies have lost their diplomatic function and have turned, with the exception of a few small representational tasks, into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore this.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it in public violates the vocation of hypocrisy, and serves to cast American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that an x-factor hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world deals a major blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Moreover, the scandal brings distress to the & quot; executioner, rather than the victims.
But let's focus on the more profound nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell's day, you could pool all your power like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have been proved perfectly correct since then, when you can control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction done, the hotel visited, the highway chosen, and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of power.
However, if one considers what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, then the control corridor ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can discover the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets hold?
True, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi's or Merkel' s character is basically a secret free of secrecy, since it divulges the public sphere; but to reveal, WikiLeaks-style, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets is to strip them of all power.
WikiLeaks has not wronged Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has wronged Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult inflicted on such a tremendous power?
It is obvious that in the future, States will no longer put any reserved information online - it would be like putting a notice on a street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with the current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to keep confidential reports about telephone secret.
Nothing is easier than knowing if and when a Head of State has travelled on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could we maintain private relationships in the future that are only for certain ears?
I am well aware that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romanticism, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents secretly pacing themselves along uncontrollable routes, carrying their communications nowhere but in their bare memory, and also hiding the few written pieces of information they have received in their shoe heel.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the espionage attempt of Watergate had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that today technology is advancing like a cancer, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructs a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) video cassettes had enabled the film researchers to explore a film tape by tape, by winding from back to front and revealing all the secrets of the montage, whereas nowadays the (numerical) CDs allow nothing more than to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, in macro portions.
High-speed trains take you from Rome to Milan in three hours, while flying takes three and a half hours, including connecting flights.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to the car and the horse.
A last observation.
In former times the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At the moment, it is the embassies requesting confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is beautifying its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to investigate compliance with the fast-moving funding promises (also known as & quot; Fast Start & quot; or Early Financing) made by developing countries.
And already rude French gossip has been exposed.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, developing countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised €7.2 billion over three years, while France has promised €1.26 billion (€420 million per annum).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to convince its partners of the fact of its commitment to Fast Start financing: detailed procedure report of its Member States, press conference, major side-events, distribution of brochures.
Operation Transparency is remarkable, and is valued precisely for its inherent value: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries doing the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces to have released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, putting it on the right track to pay respect to its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
This money, according to the Copenhagen Treaty, should be 'new' and 'additional' in order to ensure that an extra contribution was made without being to the detriment of ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what & quot; means new and additionally & quot;.
While the EU Commission proposed harmonization, certain Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone selects the benchmark that they think is best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen the benchmark for 2009: to maintain international funding, adding & quot; Fast-Start funding worth 150 million over three years.
Other countries have adopted similar benchmarks, either in terms of years or in terms and conditions at ODA level.
In return, France considered the funding of all new & quot; projects of 2010 to be 'new' and in addition 'quot;'.
In other words, there are no benchmarks for the previous year's expenditure or for ODA at global level.
Specifically, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France claims to be honouring its commitment to provide both new and additional & quot; financing.
Another, crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule over this yet, and everyone selects their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, have 1 borrowed €as the equivalent of 1 donated €.
Obviously, it is difficult to defend: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often carbon mitigation projects based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceitful to present the Euro as the equivalent of one donated Euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan to the donor country should be counted as the commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing but the following consideration: it & quot; respects its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to see for itself.
France is the only EU country to use large-scale loans.
Germany is charging 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are paying 100% in donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its obligations, France gives just 10 cents, which is a comparable amount.
Beautiful hocus pocus!
In short, France is operating a double fraud in its Fast Start funding: one part is the evolution of the action over time, and the other is the reality of the financial commitment.
France manages to make us believe that it has spent 420 million euros, new and additional, in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
Manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who conducted the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once inside the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing only a small question in a relatively short period of time compared to the totality of discussions on climate.
But it might be one drop too many in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that this will not be the case.
Be that as it may, it is imperative to learn the lesson of this first year of premature funding.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its way of posting for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and of compensatory justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could advance the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another crucial topic currently being discussed): it cannot escape the question of the transferability of loans.
France could change its position to be just as progressive on the issues as it is on other things.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about the Fast-Start of France and its vision of & quot; accountability & quot; as well as the use of loans would by its very nature raise the international confidence level that is necessary for further discussion.
Alarm - Child-ingested Pesticides
A child of 10 years of age consumes 81 different chemicals over the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association Générations Futures (former movement for the protection of the rights and respect for generations to come).
The association, which declares that its results do not reflect a statistically significant value due to the small number of samples analyzed, but are an illustration of the problematic matter discussed, purchased the food usually consumed by a child of approximately 10 years with meals plus a snack at supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh pieces of fruit and fruit, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - were studied as well as snacking by laboratories in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The dish balance is devastating: 81 chemicals, including 42 possibly or likely carcinogenic and five safely carcinogenic, as well as 37 endocrine disruptors, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Center.
& quot; Even though, in the approximate totality of cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually are not exceeded, it is quite clear from this survey that the reality of consumers potentially being exposed to carcinogenic substances or endocrine disruptor is a cause for concern, & quot; notes the association.
At breakfast time alone, the butter and the tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues, three of the residues are safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than 20 residues that can affect the endocrine system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, contains traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, for which the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
There were also minced steak, canned tuna, even baguette and chewing gum covered in pesticides and other chemicals.
In the case of tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the & quot; richest with 34 detected chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not unencumbered.
The risk of this' quot; pollutant cocktail 'to the consumer' quot; is likely to be undervalued ', the study found.
For its part, the & quot; Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts & quot; (EE-LV), in view of the urgency of the situation, has proposed to & quot; introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to halt the & quot; epidemic of diseases affecting civilization.
In July, a study conducted by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) on the presence of residues identified 365 different pesticides found in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
